<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI><UNDER>REASSESSMENTS UNDER APPEAL</UNDER></TI>
<P>2. Total Energy Services Inc, (&ldquo;TESI&rdquo;) appeals from Notices of Reassessment issued by the Minister of National Revenue (the &ldquo;Minister&rdquo;) on August 27, 2015, with respect to the 2010 and 2011 taxation years (the &ldquo;Reassessments&rdquo;) under the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> (Canada) (the &ldquo;Act&rdquo;).</P>
<P>3. TESI served Notices of Objection (the &ldquo;Objections&rdquo;) to each of the Reassessments on the Minister in a timely fashion on or about October 22, 2015.</P>
<P>4. More than 90 days have elapsed since the date the Objections were served. The Minister has not notified TESI that the Reassessments have been vacated or confirmed, nor has the Minister issued a further reassessment in respect of either the 2010 or 2011 taxation year. Accordingly, TESI brings this appeal pursuant to paragraph 169(1)(b) of the Act.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI><UNDER>MATERIAL FACTS</UNDER></TI>
<P>5. TESI is a taxable Canadian corporation as defined in subsection 89(1) of the Act. TESI is the successor by amalgamation of Total Energy Services Ltd. (&ldquo;TESL&rdquo;) and Total Energy Services Inc. (&ldquo;New Total&rdquo;). New Total was the successor to Biomerge Industries Ltd. (&ldquo;Biomerge&rdquo;) by name change.</P>
<P>6. TESI is the ultimate successor of the conversion of the Total Energy Services Trust from a trust to a corporation, which conversion occurred on May 20, 2009 pursuant to a plan of arrangement.</P>
<P>7. TESI is a body corporate which at all relevant times had a fiscal year-end of December 31. It carries on the business, directly or indirectly through its subsidiaries, of the provision of contract drilling services, the rental and transportation of surface equipment used in oil and natural gas drilling and production processes and the manufacturing, sale, rental and servicing of natural gas compression and process equipment to oil and gas exploration and production companies in western Canada and internationally.</P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Total Conversion</TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Conversion Required by Change of Law</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>8. On October 31, 2006, the Minister of Finance (&ldquo;Finance&rdquo;) announced its intention to &ldquo;level the playing field between income trusts and corporations&rdquo; by proposing a distribution tax on specified investment flow through trusts (&ldquo;SIFT&rdquo;). These proposals became law on June 22, 2007 (the &ldquo;SIFT Rules&rdquo;) and, subject to adhering to the normal growth guidelines, applied to certain trusts commencing in 2011.</P>
<P>9. The SIFT Rules effectively required that a SIFT convert to a corporation by December 31, 2010 or be subject to a new distribution tax and limitations on future growth.</P>
<P>10. On July 14, 2008, Finance introduced comprehensive draft legislation which permitted a mutual fund trust to convert to a corporation on a tax-deferred basis (the &ldquo;Conversion Rules&rdquo;). The Conversion Rules became law and provided two methods to convert from a trust to a corporation&mdash;namely, the &ldquo;exchange method&rdquo; or the &ldquo;distribution method&rdquo;.</P>
<P>11. The Conversion Rules did not place limitations with respect to the corporation that could be used to undertake the conversion nor did they specify a rule that would deem control of a corporation to have been acquired in relation to the exchange method.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Conversion by Plan of Arrangement</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>12. Total Energy Services Trust (&ldquo;Total Trust&rdquo;) was an unincorporated open ended trust governed by the laws of the Province of Alberta and created pursuant to a deed of trust dated March 23, 2005 between Olympia Trust Company and TESL. At all relevant times, Total Trust was a &ldquo;mutual fund trust&rdquo; for the purposes of the Act.</P>
<P>13. Total Trust's units were listed and posted for trading on the TSX from May 2005 until May 2009 when, pursuant to a reorganization, the units ceased trading. Until completion of such reorganization, Total Trust's business was conducted through a number of direct and indirect subsidiaries, including TESL and Bidell Equipment Limited Partnership (&ldquo;Bidell LP&rdquo;).</P>
<P>14. Total Energy Services Commercial Trust (the &ldquo;SubTrust&rdquo;) was an unincorporated trust established pursuant to the laws of the Province of Alberta. Sub-Trust was a &ldquo;unit trust&rdquo; as described in subsection 108(2) of the Act. All of Sub-Trust's units were owned by Total Trust. Prior to being wound up, the SubTrust held a 86% partnership interest in Bidell LP while Total Trust held a 14% partnership interest in Bidell LP.</P>
<P>15. TESL was a corporation which between April 29, 2005 and May 20, 2009, was a wholly-owned subsidiary of Total Trust. From May 20, 2009 to December 31, 2009, TESL was a subsidiary of Biomerge Industries Ltd., which on May 20, 2009 changed its name to Total Energy Services Inc. (herein &ldquo;New Total&rdquo;).</P>
<P>16. Total Trust was a SIFT under the SIFT Rules and Total Trust determined that to avoid the STFT Rules it was in the best interests of Total Trust to convert into a corporation pursuant to one of the mandated methods to undertake a conversion transaction under the Conversion Rules (the &ldquo;Total Conversion&rdquo;).</P>
<P>17. The Total Conversion involved the conversion of Total Trust from an income trust to a corporate structure through a Court reviewed and approved Plan of Arrangement with Biomerge. As a result of the Total Conversion and utilisation of the &ldquo;exchange method&rdquo;, holders of Total Trust's units exchanged their units for shares of New Total and Total Trust was wound-up. On May 27, 2009, the New Total shares commenced trading on the TSX under the symbol &ldquo;TOT&rdquo;.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Court Approval of the Plan of Arrangement</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>18. On March 19, 2009, Total Trust, TESL and Biomcrge entered into an agreement (the &ldquo;Arrangement Agreement&rdquo;), subsequently amended and restated April 15, 2009. Pursuant to the Arrangement Agreement, among other things, Total Trust was to be converted from an income trust to a corporation pursuant to a statutory plan of arrangement under Section 193 of the <EM>Business Corporations Act</EM> (Alberta) (the &ldquo;Plan of Arrangement&rdquo; and the &ldquo;ABCA&rdquo;),</P>
<P>19. The Arrangement Agreement was entered into by Total Trust and TESL having regard to the SIFT Rules as well as the economic and industry environment at the lime and their future growth plans. In addition to avoiding the application of the SIFT Rules, the corporate structure arising from the Arrangement Agreement was anticipated to achieve a number of business objectives, including, among other things, improving access to capital markets, facilitating Total Trust/TESL's ongoing international expansion and a simplified and more efficient corporate structure.</P>
<P>20. On May 15, 2009, the Plan of Arrangement was approved on a final basis by order of the Honourable Justice G.C. Hawco of the Alberta Court of Queen's Bench (the &ldquo;Final Order&rdquo;).</P>
<P>21. On May 20, 2009 pursuant to the Final Order, which incorporated Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; of the Arrangement Agreement, the following events occurred in the order set forth below:
<P1>(a) the Total Trust Deed of Trust was amended to (i) enable the Total Trust units to be transferred to Biomerge, and (ii) facilitate the arrangement and the implementation of the steps and transactions contemplated under the Plan of Arrangement;</P1>
<P1>(b) the articles of continuance of Biomerge were amended to provide for the creation of the New Total Common Shares as a new class of shares of Biomerge;</P1>
<P1>(c) Total Trust deposited with Bennett Jones LLP, in trust, $1,271,401, an amount equal to Biomerge's liabilities and Biomerge issued to Total Trust a demand promissory note in the same amount;</P1>
<P1>(d) the 29,050,000 outstanding Total Trust units were transferred to Biomerge in exchange for 29,050,000 Biomerge (New Total) Common Shares on a tax-deferred basis pursuant to subsections 85.1(7) and (8) of the Act;</P1>
<P1>(e) the 248,941,152 outstanding Biomerge voting common shares were transferred to Biomerge for cancellation in exchange for; (i) 56,730 New Total Common Shares, and (ii) $702,293 cash consideration;</P1>
<P1>(f) the 435,647,055 outstanding Biomerge noil-voting shares were transferred to Biomerge in exchange for cash consideration of $1,695,185;</P1>
<P1>(g) Biomerge changed its name to Total Energy Services Inc. (&ldquo;New Total&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>(h) the by-laws of TESL became the by-laws of New Total;</P1>
<P1>(i) the directors of TESL replaced the existing directors of Biomerge;</P1>
<P1>(j) the officers of TESL replaced the existing officers of Biomerge.</P1></P>
<P>22. On May 20, 2009, subsequent to the Plan of Arrangement but not pursuant to the Plan of Arrangement, the following transactions, among others, occurred:
<P1>(a) the Sub-Trust was wound up into Total Trust on a tax deferred basis pursuant to subsection 88.1(2) of the Act;</P1>
<P1>(h) the Total Trust was wound-up into New Total on a tax-deferred basis pursuant to Subsection 88.1(2) of the Act.</P1></P>
<P>23. As a result of the wind-ups, all of the assets of Total Trust were distributed to New Total.</P>
<P>24. On January 1, 2010 New Total and TESL amalgamated on a tax deferred basis pursuant to section 87 of the Act with the ongoing business operating under the name Total Energy Services Inc. (herein &ldquo;TESI&rdquo;).</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>Previous Creditors Company Arrangement Act Transactions</TI>
<P>25. Biomerge was a corporation continued under the ABCA. It was previously known as Xillix Technologies Corp. (&ldquo;Xillix&rdquo;) but changed its name to Biomerge on September 24, 2007.</P>
<P>26. Cavalon Capital Partners Ltd. (&ldquo;Cavalon&rdquo;) was a private, Calgary-based investment corporation. At all times Cavalon and its principles were arm's length with TESI, TESL, Total Trusl and all related persons.</P>
<P>27. On October 23, 2006, as a result of the demand letter from a secured creditor, Xillix sought and obtained an Order of the British Columbia Supreme Court (the &ldquo;Court&rdquo;) granting it protection from creditors under the <EM>Companies' Creditors Arrangement Act</EM> (the &ldquo;CCAA&rdquo;). The Court order gave Xillix an opportunity to develop a reorganization plan, thereby providing Xillix with an opportunity to maximize value for its stakeholders.</P>
<P>28. The initial Order of the Court was extended multiple times. The extension of the initial Order provided Xillix with more time to develop and implement a reorganisation plan.</P>
<P>29. On June 21, 2007, Xillix submitted to the Court its Flan of Compromise and Arrangement (the &ldquo;Restructuring Plan&rdquo;) under the CCAA.</P>
<P>30. On July 9, 2007, Xillix entered into an agreement (the &ldquo;Investment Agreement&rdquo;) with Cavalon. Cavalon agreed to make an investment of $4,400,000 in Xillix, structured as a non-interest bearing loan with $4,160,000 being convertible into voting and non-voting common shares in the capital of Xillix.</P>
<P>31. On September 13, 2007, Nexia Biotechnologies Ltd. acquired all of the issued and outstanding shares of Cavalon from its shareholders. The purchase price was $333,390 and was satisfied by the issuance of 1,666,950 common shares of Nexia Biotechnologies Ltd., at a price of $0.20 per share.</P>
<P>32. On September 18, 2007, Nexia Biotechnologies Ltd. and Cavalon amalgamated to form new Nexia (referred to herein as &ldquo;Nexia&rdquo;), which became Cavalon's successor in interest to the Investment Agreement.</P>
<P>33. On September 24, 2007, the Restructuring Plan was completed. Pursuant to the Restructuring Plan, the following, among other things, occurred.
<ITEM><P>Nexia subscribed for a non-interest bearing convertible note in the amount of $4,400,000 in Xiliix (the &ldquo;Convertible Note&rdquo;);</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>$3.6 million (of the $4.4 million) was used by Xillix to settle its creditors' claims;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Xillix's authorized share capital was increased by creating an unlimited number of non-voting shares and an unlimited number of preferred shares;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Approximately 94.5% (or $4,160,000) of the Convertible Note was converted into 112,023,510 common shares and 435,647,055 non-voting shares of Xillix;</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Xillix changed its name to Biomerge; and</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>On September 26, 2007 Biomerge's shares were delisted from the Toronto Stock Exchange and listed on the NEX, under the symbol &ldquo;BIL.H&rdquo;. The non-voting shares were not listed.</P></ITEM></P>
<P>34. After the Restructuring Plan was completed:
<P1>(i) Nexia held approximately 45% of Biomerge's common shares, then issued and outstanding; and</P1>
<P1>(ii) Nexia held approximately 100% of Biomerge's non-voting shares then issued and outstanding.</P1></P>
<P>35. The matters referred to in paragraphs 29 to 33 above are collectively referred to as the CCAA Plan Transactions.</P>
<P>36. At December 31, 2007, Biomerge had 248,941,152 voting common shares and 435,647,055 non-voting shares issued and outstanding. The common shares and nonvoting shares ranked equally as to dividend rights and rights on liquidation and the nonvoting were convertible to common shares on a one-to-one basis.</P>
<P>37. At the end of December 31, 2008, Biomerge had the following tax attributes:
<P1>(a) non-capital losses of $49,206,127;</P1>
<P1>(b) a capital loss carry-forward of $2,632,626;</P1>
<P1>(c) an undeducted investment tax credit (ITC) of $1,717,117 (attributed to scientific research and experimental development (SR&amp;ED) expenditures);</P1>
<P1>(d) an available SR&amp;ED expenditure pool of $23,229,238;</P1>
<P1>In addition, its wholly owned subsidiary, Xillix Imaging Ltd. had the following tax attributes:</P1>
<P1>(e) non-capital losses in the amount of $2,473,258.</P1>
<P1>(collectively the &ldquo;Tax Attributes&rdquo;).</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>Tax Filings</TI>
<P>38. The income tax return for New Total for its taxation year ending December 31, 2009 was filed in accordance with the provisions of the Act. New Total recognized the Tax Attributes in calculating its taxable income and applied the following amounts of the Tax Attributes:
<P1>(a) non capital losses in the amount of $20,130,545.</P1></P>
<P>39. At the end of December 31, 2009, New Total had the following remaining Tax Attributes:
<P1>(a) non-capital losses of $29,075,582;</P1>
<P1>(b) capital loss carry-forward of $2,632,626;</P1>
<P1>(c) undeducted ITC of $1,717,117 (attributed to SR&amp;ED expenditures); and</P1>
<P1>(d) available SR&amp;ED expenditure pool of $23,229,238.</P1></P>
<P>40. At the end of December 31, 2009, TESL had the following tax attributes:
<P1>(a) non-capital losses of $19,321,810; and</P1>
<P1>(b) undeductcd ITC of $3,212 (attributed to SR&amp;ED expenditures).</P1></P>
<P>41. On January 1, 2010, New Total and TESL amalgamated on a tax deferred basis under section 87 of the Act, with the ongoing business operating under the name TESI. Pursuant to the amalgamation, the tax pools of New Total and TESL became the tax pools of TESI. Accordingly, TESI had the following tax pools on January 1, 2010, which included the remaining unutilized Tax Attributes:
<P1>(a) non-capital losses of $48,397,392;</P1>
<P1>(b) capital loss carry-forward of $2,632,626;</P1>
<P1>(c) undeducted ITC of $1,720,329 (attributed to SR&amp;ED expenditures); and</P1>
<P1>(d) available SR&amp;ED expenditure pool of $23,229,238.</P1></P>
<P>42. The income tax return for TESI for its taxation year ending December 31, 2010 was filed in accordance with the provisions of the Act. In computing its income tax liability under Part I of the Act for its taxation year ending December 31, 2010 TESI deducted, among other things, non-capital losses of prior years in the amount of $2,878,871.</P>
<P>43. At the end of December 31, 2010, TESI had the following tax pools, which included the remaining unutilized Tax Attributes:
<P1>(a) non-capital losses of $45,518,521;</P1>
<P1>(b) capital loss carry-forward of $2,632,626;</P1>
<P1>(c) undeducted ITC of $1,720,329 (attributed to SR&amp;ED expenditures); and</P1>
<P1>(d) available SR&amp;ED expenditure pool of $23,229,238.</P1></P>
<P>44. The income tax return for TEST for its taxation year ending December 31, 2011 was filed in accordance with the provisions of the Act. In computing its income tax liability under Part I of the Act for its taxation year ending December 31, 2011 TESI deducted, among other things, non-capital losses and net capital losses from prior tax years and SR&amp;ED expenditures previously incurred as follows:
<P1>(a) non-capital losses from prior years in the amount of $27,457,957;</P1>
<P1>(b) capital losses from prior years in the amount of $694,848 (being net capital losses of $347,424); and</P1>
<P1>(c) SR&amp;ED expenditures previously incurred in the amount of $23,229,238.</P1></P>
<P>45. At the end of December 31, 2011, TESI had the following tax pools, which included the remaining unutilized Tax Attributes:
<P1>(a) non-capital losses of $18,060,564;</P1>
<P1>(b) capital loss carry-forward of $1,937,778; and</P1>
<P1>(c) undeducted ITC of $1,720,329 (attributed to SR&amp;ED expenditures).</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>The Reassessments</TI>
<P>46. The Minister reassessed TESl's taxation year ending December 31, 2010 by disallowing the deduction of non-capital losses of prior years in the amount of $2,878,871.</P>
<P>47. The Minister reassessed TESI's taxation year ending December 31, 2011 by:
<P1>(a) Disallowing non-capital losses from prior years in the amount of $26,196,711;</P1>
<P1>(b) Disallowing capital losses from prior years in the amount of $694,848 (being net capital losses of $347,424); and</P1>
<P1>(c) Disallowing the deduction of SR&amp;ED expenditures previously incurred in the amount of $23,229,238.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI>Basis of Reassessment</TI>
<P>48. By letter dated April 13, 2015 (the &ldquo;First Proposal Letter&rdquo;), the Minister proposed to reassess on the basis that TESI (and its predecessors) were not entitled to utilize the Tax Attributes in the calculation of taxable income, based on the following position:
<P1>(a) That for the purposes of section 245 of the Act a &ldquo;tax benefit&rdquo; arose by virtue of the non-impairment of the Tax Attributes;</P1>
<P1>(b) That for the purposes of section 245 of the Act that the relevant &ldquo;series of transactions&rdquo; included not only the Total Conversion but also the CCAA Plan Transactions as well as certain post Total Conversion transactions and certain of the transactions within the &ldquo;series of transactions&rdquo; were not undertaken &ldquo;primarily for <EM>bona fide</EM> purposes other than to obtain the tax benefit&rdquo; and thus were avoidance transaction(s) for the purposes of section 245; and</P1>
<P1>(c) That the purported avoidance transaction(s) constituted an abuse of the Act read as a whole.</P1></P>
<P>49. In a subsequent letter dated July 9, 2015 (the &ldquo;Second Proposal Letter&rdquo;) the Minister restated its position to be that the CCAA Plan Transactions were distinguishable from the Total Conversion and any post Total Conversion transactions, however that section 245 of the Act applied to the CCAA Plan Transactions so as to determine the Tax Attributes of Biomerge (after the CCAA Plan Transactions) to be nil. In the alternative it relied on its position as set out in the First Proposal Letter.</P>
<P>50. Although the Reassessments purported to disallow the Tax Attributes. In fact, in reassessing, the Minister disallowed an amount inaddition to the Tax Attributes of $24,668. This additional amount arose because of the Minister's mistaken assumption that a corporation, 33599 Yukon Ltd., was a subsidiary of Biomerge when in fact it was not (the CRA reassessed amounts collectively referred to as the &ldquo;Disputed Amounts&rdquo;).</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI><UNDER>ISSUES TO BE DECIDED</UNDER></TI>
<P>51. The issues to be decided are:
<P1>(a) Whether section 245 of the Act applies to the CCAA Plan Transactions so as to result in the denial of the use of any of the Tax Attributes claimed by the Appellant;</P1>
<P1>(b) Whether section 245 of the Act applies to the Total Conversion so as to result in the denial of the use of any of the Tax Attributes claimed by the Appellant;</P1>
<P1>(c) Whether section 245 of the Act applies collectively to the CCAA Plan Transaction and Total Conversion so as to result in the denial of the use of any of the Tax Attributes claimed by the Appellant; and</P1>
<P1>(d) Whether the Reassessments were issued outside the &ldquo;normal reassessment period&rdquo; as defined in the Act such that the issuance of the Reassessments is statute-barred under the Act or arc otherwise outside the limitation period, as applicable in the Province of Alberta or federally, such that the Minister is estopped from issuing the Reassessments.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>E.</N><TI><UNDER>STATUTORY PROVISIONS RELIED UPON</UNDER></TI>
<P>52. The Appellant intends to rely upon, <EM>inter alia</EM>, Parts I, XVI and XVII of the Act, including sections 37, 85, 87, 88, 111, 127, 152, 169, 245, 248, 251 and 256.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>F.</N><TI><UNDER>REASONS THE APPELLANT INTENDS TO RELY UPON</UNDER></TI>
<P>53. The CCAA Plan Transactions and the Total Conversation do not result, directly or indirectly, in a tax benefit to the Appellant for the purposes of section 245 of the Act.</P>
<P>54. The Total Conversion may reasonably be considered to have been undertaken or arranged primarily for <EM>bona fide</EM> purposes other than to obtain a tax benefit and therefore the Total Conversion does not constitute an &ldquo;avoidance transaction&rdquo; for the purposes of section 245(3) of the Act.</P>
<P>55. The CCAA Plan Transactions may reasonably be considered to have been undertaken or arranged primarily for <EM>bona fide</EM> purposes other than to obtain a tax benefit and therefore the CCAA Plan Transactions did not constitute &ldquo;avoidance transactions&rdquo; for the purposes of section 245(3) of the Act.</P>
<P>56. There was no connection between the CCAA Plan Transactions and the Total Conversion.</P>
<P>57. The Total Conversion did not result, directly or indirectly, for the purposes of section 245 of the Act, in a misuse of any provision of the Act or an abuse having regard to the provisions of the Act, read as a whole.</P>
<P>58. The CCAA Plan Transactions did not result, directly or indirectly, for the purposes of section 245 of the Act, in a misuse of any provision of the Act or an abuse having regard to the provisions of the Act, read as a whole.</P>
<P>59. The tax consequences asserted by the Minister in the Reassessment are not reasonable in the circumstances within the meaning of subsections 245(2) and 245(5) of the Act.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>G.</N><TI><UNDER>RELIEF SOUGHT</UNDER></TI>
<P>60. The Appellant respectfully requests that this appeal be allowed with costs and that the Reassessments be vacated.</P>
<P>61. The Appellant also seeks as relief to amend discretionary deductions and any additional relief as may be available.</P>
