<BLOCK1><TI>REPLY</TI>
<P>In reply to the appellant's notice of appeal with respect to the taxation years ending December 31, 2010 and December 31, 2011, the Deputy Attorney General of Canada says:</P>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>1. He admits the facts stated in paragraphs 3, 4, 5, 6, 12, 13, 14, 15, 18, 23, 25, 27, 29, 31, 32, 33, 34, 36, 46 and 47 of the notice of appeal.</P>
<P>2. He denies the facts alleged in paragraphs 7 to 11, 19, 22, 24, 26, 30, 37 to 45 and 48 to 50 of the notice of appeal.</P>
<P>3. He has no knowledge of, and puts in issue, the facts alleged in paragraphs 20 and 28 of the notice of appeal.</P>
<P>4. With respect to paragraph 16 of the notice of appeal, he:
<P1>a) Admits that Total Energy Services Trust (&ldquo;<BOLD>Total Trust</BOLD>&rdquo;) was a specified investment flow-through trust (&ldquo;<BOLD>SIFT</BOLD>&rdquo;) under the SIFT Rules; and</P1>
<P1>b) has no knowledge of whether Total Trust determined that to avoid the SIFT Rules it was in the best interest of Total Trust to convert into a corporation pursuant to one of the mandated methods to undertake a conversion transaction under the Conversion Rules.</P1></P>
<P>5. He admits only that the facts stated in paragraph 17 of the notice of appeal are a general overview description of the conversion of Total Trust from an income trust to a corporate structure.</P>
<P>6. He admits the facts stated in paragraph 21 of the notice of appeal but states that the description of events is incomplete.</P>
<P>7. With respect to paragraph 35 of the notice of appeal, he states that the description of the CCAA Plan Transactions by reference to paragraphs 29 to 33 of the notice of appeal is incomplete.</P>
<P>8. To the extent that there are allegations of fact stated under the heading &ldquo;Reasons&rdquo; in the notice of appeal, he denies those allegations.</P>
<P>9. The Minister of National Revenue initially assessed the appellant (sometimes referred to as &ldquo;<BOLD>TESI</BOLD>&rdquo;) for the taxation years ending December 31, 2010 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>2010 taxation year</BOLD>&rdquo;) and December 31, 2011 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>2011 taxation year</BOLD>&rdquo;) on September 1, 2011 and June 29, 2012, respectively, and accordingly issued notices on those dates.</P>
<P>10. The Minister reassessed the appellant for the 2010 and 2011 taxation years on August 27, 2015 to disallow non-capital losses, net capital losses and SR&amp;ED expenditures on the basis that section 245 of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Act</BOLD>&rdquo;) applied to transactions referred to as the &ldquo;CCAA Plan Transactions&rdquo; and the &ldquo;Total Conversion Transactions&rdquo; (described further below), as follows:
