<BLOCK3><TI>Assumptions</TI>
<P>11. In determining the appellant's tax liabilities for the 2010 and 2011 taxation years, the Minister made the following assumptions of fact:</P>
<BLOCK4><TI>Xillix Technologies Corp.</TI>
<P><P1>a) Xillix Technologies Corp. (&ldquo;<BOLD>Xillix</BOLD>&rdquo;) was formed on November 2, 1990 by the amalgamation of Microscan Imaging and Instrumentation Inc. and Endoscan Scientific Instrument Corporation pursuant to the <EM>British Columbia Company Act</EM>.</P1>
<P1>b) Xillix was, at all material times, a public corporation and its shares were listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange until its shares were delisted on September 26, 2007 and listed on the NEX.</P1>
<P1>c) Xillix was engaged in the research, development and commercialization of fluorescence endoscopy for the improved detection and localization of cancer.</P1>
<P1>d) On October 23, 2006, after receiving a demand letter from a secured creditor for repayment of its long-term debt, Xillix filed for and received creditor protection under the <EM>Companies' Creditors Arrangement Act</EM> (&ldquo;CCAA&rdquo;) pursuant to an order issued by the Supreme Court of British Columbia. The court order gave Xillix an opportunity to develop a reorganization plan, thereby providing the company with an opportunity to maximize value for its stakeholders.</P1>
<P1>e) The initial order of the BC Supreme Court was extended multiple times and provided Xillix with more time to develop and implement a reorganization plan.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>Total Energy Services Trust</TI>
<P><P1>f) The Total Energy Services Trust (described previously as the Total Trust) was established as an open-end unincorporated mutual fund trust under the laws of Alberta pursuant to a deed of trust dated March 23, 2005 between Olympia Trust Company and Total Energy Services Ltd. (&ldquo;<BOLD>TESL</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P1>
<P1>g) The units of the Total Trust were listed and traded on the TSX from May 2005 until May 2009.</P1>
<P1>h) The business of the Total Trust was conducted through a number of direct and indirect subsidiaries, including TESL and Bidell LP.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>Total Energy Services Ltd.</TI>
<P><P1>i) TESL was a corporation amalgamated under the laws of Alberta.</P1>
<P1>j) Between April 28, 2005 and May 20, 2009, TESL was a wholly owned subsidiary of the Total Trust.</P1>
<P1>k) TESL was in the business of the provision of contract drilling services, the rental and transportation of surface equipment used in drilling and production processes and the manufacturing, sale, rental and servicing of natural gas compression equipment to oil and gas exploration and production companies in western Canada.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>Total Energy Services Commercial Trust</TI>
<P><P1>l) The Total Energy Services Commercial Trust (the &ldquo;Sub-Trust&rdquo;) was an unincorporated trust established pursuant to the laws of Alberta. Sub-Trust was a &lsquo;unit trust&rsquo; (as described in subsection 108(2) of the Act) and all of its units were owned by the Total Trust.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>Cavalon Capital Partners Ltd.</TI>
<P><P1>m) Cavalon Capital Partners Ltd. (&ldquo;<BOLD>Cavalon</BOLD>&rdquo;) was, at all material times, a private Calgary based investment corporation amalgamated under the laws of Alberta.</P1>
<P1>n) The shares of Cavalon were owned by Greg Matthews and Lisa Tonken (the spouse of David Tonken), each as to 50%.</P1>
<P1>o) Mr. Matthews and Mr. Tonken were the managing directors of Cavalon.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
