<P1>q) On December 11, 2006, Mr. Matthews and Mr. Tonken, on behalf of Cavalon, submitted a proposal to acquire Xillix' tax pools for $0.055 per dollar of useable tax loss. In line with Cavalon's business, the intent was to acquire Xillix in a form such that Xillix' tax pools could subsequently be sold by Cavalon to a profitable company that was looking to shelter its taxable income.</P1>
<P1>r) As at December 31, 2006, Xillix had 136,917,642 issued and outstanding common voting shares.</P1>
<P1>s) On January 3, 2007, Cavalon submitted a revised proposal regarding Xillix (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Letter of Agreement</BOLD>&rdquo;), which was accepted by Xillix on January 5, 2007.</P1>
<P1>t) Under the Letter of Agreement:
<P2>i) Cavalon offered to invest in Xillix by way of a convertible debenture (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Debenture</BOLD>&rdquo;);</P2>
<P2>ii) the amount of the Debenture was to be calculated by multiplying Xillix's useable tax losses times $0.055;</P2>
<P2>iii) the Debenture would provide that Cavalon could convert 96% of the Debenture into one or more classes of voting and nonvoting equity shares of Xillix resulting in Cavalon holding 80% of the equity shares and 45% of the voting shares of Xillix;</P2>
<P2>iv) the current shareholders of Xillix would hold 20% of the equity and 55% of the voting shares of Xillix immediately following the conversion of the Debenture;</P2>
<P2>v) the directors and officers of Xillix would resign and be replaced by nominees of Cavalon; and</P2>
<P2>vi) of the funds received by Xillix pursuant to the financing, $800,000 would be retained by Xillix to provide it with sufficient capital to maintain itself as a publicly traded company, maintain its listing on a stock exchange and combine itself with another entity that would utilize its tax pools.</P2></P1>
<P1>u) In April 2007, Mr. Matthews and Mr. Tonken were appointed to the Board of Directors of Xillix. Mr. Matthews also became the Corporate Secretary and Chief Financial Officer (CFO) of Xillix. Mr. Tonken became the President and CEO of Xillix.</P1>
<P1>v) On May 3, 2007, Xillix completed the sale of most of its assets consisting of all of its intellectual property, as well as substantially all of its capital assets and inventories for proceeds totalling $3 million. Thereafter, Xillix had no operating business or assets other than cash and other nominal assets.</P1>
<P1>w) On June 21, 2007, Xillix submitted its Plan of Compromise and Arrangement (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Restructuring Plan</BOLD>&rdquo;) to the court under the CCAA.</P1>
<P1>x) On July 9, 2007, Xillix entered into a definitive agreement (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Cavalon Agreement</BOLD>&rdquo;) with Cavalon. Cavalon agreed to provide funds in the amount of $4,400,000 to Xillix, structured as a non-interest bearing loan with $4,160,000 being convertible into voting and non-voting common shares in the capital of Xillix (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Convertible Loan</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P1>
<P1>y) The amount of $4.4 million was computed based on a multiple of Xillix' tax losses for 2006.</P1>
<P1>z) Mr. Tonken was also the President and CEO of Nexia Biotechnologies Ltd. (&ldquo;<BOLD>Nexia</BOLD>&rdquo;). And Mr. Matthews was a member of Nexia's Board of Directors.</P1>
<P1>aa) On September 12, 2007, Nexia entered into an agreement with Cavalon's shareholders to acquire all of the issued and outstanding shares of Cavalon. The purchase price was $333,390 and was satisfied by the issuance of 1,666,950 common shares of Nexia at a price of $0.20 per share. Cavalon's only significant asset was the Cavalon Agreement.</P1>
<P1>bb) The 1,666,950 Nexia shares (received as consideration for the Cavalon shares) were placed in Escrow, pending the closing of a transaction between Xillix and a third party.</P1>
<P1>cc) On September 18, 2007, Nexia and Cavalon amalgamated to form Nexia Biotechnologies Ltd. (&ldquo;<BOLD>New Nexia</BOLD>&rdquo;), which became Cavalon's successor in interest to the Cavalon Agreement.</P1>
<P1>dd) On September 24, 2007, the Restructuring Plan was completed. Pursuant to the Restructuring Plan, the following occurred:
<P2>i) New Nexia made a non-interest bearing loan of $4,400,000 to Xillix (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Convertible Loan</BOLD>&rdquo;);</P2>
<P2>ii) $3.6 million (of the $4.4 million) was used by Xillix to settle its creditors' claims;</P2>
<P2>iii) Xillix's authorized share capital was increased by creating an unlimited number of non-voting and an unlimited number of preferred shares;</P2>
<P2>iv) Approximately 94.5% (or $4,160,000) of the Convertible Loan was converted into 112,023,510 common shares and 435,647,055 non-voting shares of Xillix. As a result of this transaction, New Nexia held 45% of the voting common shares and 100% of the non-voting shares (or 80% of the total equity interest) in Xillix. The remaining $240,000 loan amount was non-interest bearing, without security and repayable on demand; and</P2>
<P2>v) Xillix changed its name to Biomerge Industries Ltd. (&ldquo;<BOLD>Biomerge</BOLD>&rdquo;);</P2></P1>
<P1>ee) On September 26, 2007, the shares of Biomerge were delisted from the Toronto Stock Exchange and listed on the NEX, under the symbol &ldquo;BIL.H&rdquo;. The non-voting shares of Biomerge were not listed.</P1>
<P1>ff) At December 31, 2007, Biomerge had 248,941,152 voting common shares and 435,647,055 non-voting shares issued and outstanding. The common shares and non-voting shares ranked equally as to dividend rights and rights on liquidation. The non-voting shares were convertible to common shares on a one-to-one basis.</P1>
<P1>gg) As a result of the Restructuring Plan, Biomerge had no operating business, had no assets other than cash and other nominal assets and was indebted to New Nexia in the amount of $240,000.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
