<P1>uu) From January 1, 2009 to May 20, 2009, TESL incurred an interest expense of $3,486,000 on amounts owing to the Total Trust, all of which was included in the Total Trust's income (before allocations) for the year then ended. The $3,486,000 represented the Total Trust's only source of income for the year. All of the Total Trust's income was allocated to the Total Trust's unitholders.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>Effective Date of Arrangement and Following Transactions</TI>
<P><P1>vv) The Arrangement became effective on May 20, 2009 and the events described in paragraph 11(rr) above occurred.</P1>
<P1>ww) On May 27, 2009, the New Total Common Shares commenced trading on the TSX under the symbol &ldquo;TOT&rdquo;.</P1>
<P1>xx) After the effective date of the Plan of Arrangement, and in particular on May 20, 2009, the Sub-Trust and the Total Trust were wound-up pursuant to subsection 88.1(2) of the Act.</P1>
<P1>yy) As a result of the wind-up, all of the assets of the Total Trust became assets of New Total, including the $213,469,860 Trust Debenture owing from TESL.</P1>
<P1>zz) From May 21 to December 31, 2009, TESL incurred an additional interest expense of $19,738,652 on the Trust Debenture.</P1>
<P1>aaa) The Trust Debenture was settled on December 31, 2009.</P1>
<P1>bbb) The $23,224,652 aggregate interest expense ($3,486,000 + $19,738,652) incurred by TESL on the Trust Debenture contributed to TESL's net loss of $25,992,248 (before a further $1,226,300 reduction for the section 110.5 election) for its taxation year ended December 31, 2009.</P1>
<P1>ccc) At the end of December 31, 2009, TESL had: (i) a non-capital loss of $19,321,810 (after carrying back a loss of $7,896,738 to its December 31, 2008 taxation year); and (ii) an undeducted ITC of $3,212 (attributed to SR&amp;ED expenditures).</P1>
<P1>ddd) New Total included the $19,738,652 of interest income in its total net income of $20,130,545 for the 2009 taxation year. New Total applied non-capital losses from previous years of $20,130,545 to reduce its taxable income to nil.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>For clarity, the Deputy Attorney General states that the non-capital loss applied by New Total for the 2009 taxation year was not disallowed by the Minister. The 2009 taxation year was statute-barred by the time the Minister reassessed the 2010 and 2011 taxation years.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>eee) At the end of December 31, 2009, New Total had: (i) a remaining non-capital loss of $29,075,582 (computed as $49,206,127&mdash;$20,130,545); (ii) a capital loss carry-forward of $2,632,626; (iii) an undeducted ITC of $1,717,117 (attributed to SR&amp;ED expenditures); and (iv) an available SR&amp;ED expenditure pool of $23,229,238.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>Amalgamation of New Total and TESL</TI>
<P><P1>fff) On January 1, 2010, New Total and TESL amalgamated to form Total Energy Services Inc. (i.e., the appellant or &ldquo;<BOLD>TESI</BOLD>&rdquo;). Pursuant to the amalgamation, the tax pools of New Total and TESL became those of the appellant. Accordingly, the appellant had the following tax attributes (collectively the &ldquo;<BOLD>TESI Tax Attributes</BOLD>&rdquo;):
<P2>i) non-capital losses of $48,397,392 ($29,075,582 + $19,321,810);</P2>
<P2>ii) capital loss carry-forwards of $2,632,626;</P2>
<P2>iii) undeducted ITC's of $1,720,329 attributed to SR&amp;ED expenditures ($1,717,117 + $3,212); and</P2>
<P2>iv) an SR&amp;ED expenditure pool of $23,229,238.</P2></P1>
<P1>ggg) In January 2010, the appellant replaced its credit facilities with a $10 million revolving operating facility and an $80 million revolving term loan facility. The appellant's obligation under the facilities was secured by a first fixed and floating charge on all assets of the company, its wholly owned subsidiaries and partnerships and certain other collateral security. The rate at which the facilities bore interest ranged from prime plus 1.25% to 2.00%.</P1>
<P1>hhh) On January 15, 2010, the appellant completed the previously announced acquisition of the oilfield service, rental and transportation business conducted by DC Energy Services LP (&ldquo;<BOLD>DC Energy</BOLD>&rdquo;) for $44.4 million. The cash portion of the purchase price of $31.9 million was financed using the appellant's credit facilities and the balance of the purchase price of $12.5 million was financed through the issuance of an unsecured convertible debenture bearing interest at 5% per annum, maturing on June 30, 2012.</P1>
<P1>iii) On February 9, 2011, the appellant issued $69 million of principal convertible unsecured subordinated debentures that bore interest at 5.75%.</P1>
<P1>jjj) On February 17, 2011, the appellant secured a $35 million operating facility with a major Canadian financial institution bearing interest at prime plus 0.50%.</P1>
<P1>kkk) On January 1, 2012, the appellant and Xillix Imaging Ltd., a wholly owned subsidiary, amalgamated to form Total Energy Services Inc. At the time of the amalgamation, Xillix Imaging Ltd. had non-capital losses of $2,473,258.</P1>
<P1>lll) On November 6, 2012, 33599 Yukon Inc., a wholly-owned subsidiary, was wound up into the appellant. 33599 Yukon Inc. had non-capital losses of $24,668 at the time of the amalgamation.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>Tax Returns</TI>
<P><P1>mmm) For the 2010 taxation year, the appellant reported net income of $2,878,871 and applied $2,878,871 of non-capital losses carried forward from prior years to reduce its taxable income to nil for the year.</P1>
<P1>nnn) At the end of 2010 taxation year, the appellant had non-capital losses of $45,518,521, a capital loss carry-forward of $2,632,626, an undeducted ITC of $1,720,329 and an available SR&amp;ED expenditure pool of $23,229,238.</P1>
<P1>ooo) For the 2011 taxation year, the appellant reported net income of $27,858,714, following, in part, a SR&amp;ED deduction of $23,229,238. The appellant applied $27,457,957 of non-capital losses carried forward from prior years and $694,848 of its capital losses carried forward (or $347,424 at 50%) to reduce its taxable income to $53,333.</P1>
<P1>ppp) At the end of 2011 taxation year, the appellant had non-capital losses of $18,060,564, a capital loss carry-forward of $1,937,778 and an undeducted ITC of $1,720,329.</P1>
<P1>qqq) No former business carried on by Biomerge (formerly Xillix) before May 3, 2007 was carried on for profit or with a reasonable expectation of profit by the appellant in the 2010 and 2011 taxation years.</P1>
<P1>rrr) The appellant did not earn any income in the 2010 and 2011 taxation years from any business formerly carried on by Biomerge prior to May 3, 2007 or from the sale, leasing, rental or development of similar properties to those formerly sold, leased, rented or developed by Biomerge prior to May 3, 2007 or from the rendering of services similar to those formerly rendered by Biomerge prior to May 3, 2007.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>GAAR</TI>
<P><P1>sss) The transactions outlined above including the Letter of Agreement, the Cavalon Agreement, the Restructuring Plan, the Plan of Arrangement and Arrangement were a series of transactions.</P1>
<P1>ttt) The following were avoidance transactions that resulted directly or indirectly, and were part of a series of transactions which series resulted directly or indirectly, in a tax benefit to the appellant within the meaning of subsections 245(2) and (3) of the Act (collectively the &ldquo;<BOLD>Avoidance Transactions</BOLD>&rdquo;):
<P2>i) The transactions between Cavalon and Xillix, including:
<P3>1) The proposed December 11, 2006 Letter of Agreement (and subsequent revision thereto dated January 3, 2007) by Cavalon to Xillix.</P3>
<P3>2) Xillix's acceptance of the terms of the January 3, 2007 Letter of Agreement.</P3>
<P3>3) The April 2007 appointment of Mr. Matthews and Mr. Tonken to the Board of Directors of Xillix.</P3>
<P3>4) The May 3, 2007 sale of most of Xillix's assets consisting of all of its intellectual property, as well as substantially all of its capital assets and inventories.</P3>
<P3>5) The entering into of the July 9, 2007 Cavalon Agreement, whereby Cavalon agreed to make an investment of $4,400,000 in Xillix, structured as a non-interest bearing loan with $4,160,000 being convertible into voting and non-voting common shares of Xillix.</P3></P2>
<P2>ii) The September 12, 2007 Share Purchase Agreement, whereby Nexia agreed to purchase all of the issued and outstanding shares of Cavalon in exchange for 1,666,950 common shares of Nexia (at a price of $0.20 per share), held in Escrow pending the closing of a transaction between Xillix and a third party.</P2>
<P2>iii) The September 18, 2007 Nexia and Cavalon amalgamation whereby the amalgamated entity New Nexia became the successor in interest to the Cavalon Agreement.</P2>
<P2>iv) The completion of the Restructuring Plan on September 24, 2007.</P2>
<P2>v) The entering into of the February 2, 2009 Letter of Intent in respect to the proposed business combination transaction involving the Total Trust, Biomerge and New Nexia.</P2>
<P2>vi) The entering into of the March 19, 2009 Arrangement Agreement whereby the Total Trust announced its conversion from an income trust to a corporation pursuant to the Plan of Arrangement.</P2>
<P2>vii) The February 1, 2009 interest rate change on the Trust Debenture from 10% to 2% and again on May 20, 2009, from 2% to 15%, giving rise to interest expense of $23,224,652 for TESL and a corresponding income inclusion of $3,486,000 and $19,738,652 for the Total Trust and New Total (Biomerge), respectively.</P2>
<P2>viii) The May 20, 2009 closing of the transactions listed in Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; of the Arrangement Agreement made March 19, 2009, and amended and restated April 15, 2009.</P2>
<P2>ix) The wind-up of the Total Trust and Sub-Trust on May 20, 2009.</P2>
<P2>x) The December 31, 2009 settlement of the Trust Debenture.</P2>
<P2>xi) The January 1, 2010 amalgamation of New Total and TESL to form the appellant, whereby the tax pools of each predecessor became those of the appellant.</P2></P1>
<P1>uuu) The tax benefits were the preservation, carry-forward and use of the Biomerge Tax Attributes which subsequently formed a portion of the TESI Tax Attributes resulting in the reduction, avoidance or deferral of tax by the appellant.</P1>
<P1>vvv) None of the Avoidance Transactions on their own or as part of a series of transactions could reasonably be considered to have been undertaken or arranged primarily for <EM>bona fide</EM> purposes other than to obtain a tax benefit, within the meaning of section 245 of the Act.</P1>
<P1>www) the tax consequences to the appellant that are reasonable in the circumstances to deny the tax benefit is to deny use of the TESI Tax Attributes (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Tax Consequences</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P1></P>
<P>12. In determining the appellant's tax liability for the 2010 and 2011 taxation years, the Minister considered:
<P1>a) that the general policy of the Act is to prohibit the transfer of losses between arm's length parties, subject to certain express and permissive exceptions, and that subsection 111(5) (and also the related provisions in respect of the Tax Attributes under subsections 111(4), 37(6.1) and 127(9.1) of the Act) is an anti-avoidance provision designed to prevent arm's length loss trading from an unrelated business;</P1>
<P1>b) that the purpose of the SIFT legislation proposing a distribution tax was to restore the balance and fairness to the federal tax system by effecting income tax neutrality on business profits earned by corporations and income trusts; and</P1>
<P1>c) the Minister assumed that the Conversion Rules for SIFTs, including under subsections 85.1(8), 107(3) and (3.1) of the Act, were designed to ensure that income trusts could reorganize as corporations without facing an additional tax burden at the time of conversion, but were not meant to facilitate loss trading between unrelated parties.</P1></P>
<P>13. Cavalon was engaged in the business of the monetization of tax losses through reorganizing public and private companies.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>ISSUES TO BE DECIDED</TI>
<P>14. The issues are:
<P1>a) whether the reassessments for the appellant's 2010 and 2011 taxation years were issued outside the &ldquo;normal reassessment period&rdquo;; and</P1>
<P1>b) whether section 245 of the Act applies so as to deny use of any of the TESI Tax Attributes claimed by the appellant.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>STATUTORY PROVISIONS RELIED ON</TI>
<P>15. He relies on sections 37, 85.1, 88.1, 107, 111, 122, 122.1, 127, 152, 245, 248 (including 248(10)) and 256, and subsection 69(11) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, R.S.C. 1985, c. 1 (5th Supp.), as amended.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI>GROUNDS RELIED ON AND RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P>16. The appellant has pleaded no facts or grounds respecting the issue raised in paragraph 51(d) of the notice of appeal regarding whether the reassessments were issued outside the normal reassessment period. In any event, the normal reassessment period of the appellant in respect of the 2010 and 2011 taxation years ended four-years after the date of initial assessment, in accordance with paragraph 152(3.1)(a) of the Act, as the appellant was at all material times a corporation other than a Canadian-controlled private corporation.</P>
<P>17. The Avoidance Transactions were avoidance transactions that resulted directly or indirectly, or were part of a series of transactions which resulted directly or indirectly, in tax benefits to the appellant within the meaning of subsections 245(2) and (3) of the Act.</P>
<P>18. The tax benefits were the preservation, carry-forward and use of the Biomerge Tax Attributes which subsequently formed a portion of the TESI Tax Attributes resulting in the reduction, avoidance or deferral of tax by the appellant.</P>
<P>19. None of the Avoidance Transactions on their own or as part of a series of transactions could reasonably be considered to have been undertaken or arranged primarily for <EM>bona fide</EM> purposes other than to obtain the tax benefits, within the meaning of subsections 245(1) and 245(3) of the Act.</P>
<P>20. It may reasonably be considered that the Avoidance Transactions were structured in a manner:
<P1>a) to circumvent subsections 111(4) and 111(5) (plus subsections 37(6.1) and 127(9.1)) and the general policy of the Act regarding tax attribute trading, in a manner that frustrates and defeats their object, spirit and purpose,</P1>
<P1>b) to achieve an outcome subsections 111(4) and 111(5) (plus subsections 37(6.1) and 127(9.1)) and the general policy of the Act regarding tax attribute trading were intended to prevent,</P1>
<P1>c) that defeats the underlying rationale of subsections 111(4) and 111(5) (plus subsections 37(6.1) and 127(9.1)) and the general policy of the Act regarding tax attribute trading,</P1>
<P1>d) to abuse the provisions of Act that form part of the general policy of the Act read as a whole regarding the trading of tax attributes between unrelated entities, and</P1>
<P1>e) that defeats the underlying policy of the SIFT Conversion Rules, including subsections 85.1(8) and 107(3) and (3.1).</P1></P>
<P>21. In accordance with subsections 245(2) and 245(5) of the Act, imposing the Tax Consequences to the appellant is reasonable in the circumstances in order to deny the tax benefit that would, but for section 245, result directly or indirectly from the Avoidance Transactions.</P>
<P>22. He requests that the appeals be dismissed, with costs.</P>
