<BLOCK1><TI>RESPONDENT'S WRITTEN SUBMISSIONS (RE: APPELLANT'S MOTION RETURNABLE OCTOBER 16, 2017)</TI>
<P><QUOTE><P>...In enacting the GAAR, Parliament has provided the Minister with an additional basis for reassessment of a taxpayer within the detailed structur e for reassessing set forth in the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>. Even though section 245 permits the Minister to base that reassessment on the policy of the Act rather than the explicit provisions of the Act other than section 245, <UNDER>that policy is created by Parliament and interpreted by the courts. The Minister has not been delegated any power to make policy...</UNDER><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Kaulius v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2003 FCA 371</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>appeal to the SCC dismissed in</CASEDISP><CASEREF><SOC>Mathew v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2005 SCC 55</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> [underlining added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">I. Overview</TI>
<P>1. The appellant has examined the nominee for the Crown twice and has requested and been provided numerous documents, including the audit file. There is no evidence that there are any further relevant documents regarding the reassessments at issue in this appeal.</P>
<P>2. By this motion the appellant seeks documents and information (the &ldquo;Requested Documents and Information&rdquo;) dealing with unrelated taxpayers or which were produced during the course of the audit of unrelated taxpayers. There is no evidence any of the Requested Documents and Information were produced or considered in the course of issuing the reassessments at issue in this appeal.</P>
<P>3. This Court (three times) and the Federal Court of Appeal have recently clarified the principles regarding disclosure of such documents and information and those principles make clear that the Requested Documents and Information are not producible. In fact, this Court and the FCA have already dealt with 14 of the 18 requests for documents being made in the appellant's motion. The motion should be dismissed with respect to those 14 requests, as well as the remaining four.</P>
<P>4. The Requested Documents and Information can be broken down as follows:
<P1>a. Documents and information regarding the application of the GAAR to other taxpayers (Motion Request #1; Discovery Request #4);</P1>
<P1>b. Communications between the CRA and Finance regarding changes or proposed changes to the SIFT conversion rules (Motion Request #2; Discovery Request #7);</P1>
<P1>c. Specific documents ordered to be produced by the Crown in <CASEREF><SOC>Superior Plus Corp. v. The Queen</SOC><CITE>2015 TCC 132</CITE></CASEREF> (<EM>Superior #1</EM>), <CASEREF><CITE>2015 FCA 241</CITE></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><CITE>2016 TCC 217</CITE></CASEREF> (<EM>Superior #2</EM>) (Motion Requests #3 and 6 to 18; Discovery Requests #8 and 17 to 29);</P1>
<P1>d. A memo referred to in an email dated December 5, 2014 dealing with settlement (Motion Request #4; Discovery Request #12); and</P1>
<P1>e. A copy of the approval of the GAAR Committee regarding another taxpayer (Motion Request #5; Discovery Request #16).</P1></P>
<P>5. As stated, there is no evidence any of the Requested Documents and Information were produced or considered in the course of issuing the reassessments at issue in this appeal. The recent jurisprudence makes clear they are not producible.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">II. This Court established a demarcation line in <EM>Superior Plus Corp.</EM></TI>
<P>6. The appellant's pursuit of the Requested Documents and Information is forestalled by this Court's test for relevance as set out in <EM>Superior #1</EM>, as endorsed by the FCA, and then applied by Justice Hogan in the follow-up motion in <EM>Superior #2</EM>, and by Justice V. Miller in <EM>MP Western Properties Inc.</EM> et al (<EM>MP Western</EM>).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>MP Western Properties Inc. et al v. The Queen</SOC><CITE>2017 TCC 82</CITE></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>7. In particular, in <EM>Superior #1</EM>, this Court found that the demarcation line for establishing the relevance of documents at discovery was whether the documents were either prepared directly in the context of the audit of the taxpayer or were considered by CRA officials who were charged with the audit of the taxpayer or who were consulted regarding the application of the GAAR:
<QUOTE><P>[19] ...the motion record shows that the Refused Documents were either prepared directly in the context of the audit of the Appellant or were considered by CRA officials who were charged with the audit of the Appellant or who were consulted regarding the application of the GAAR.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>8. This demarcation line served as the benchmark that was used to assess the relevance of the Refused Documents in <EM>Superior #1</EM>. This Court's analysis in <EM>Superior #1</EM> respecting Refused Document 1 is illustrative, referring to the minutes of the GAAR Committee meeting:
<QUOTE><P><UNDER>Decision</UNDER>: The redacted portion of Item 1 ... is clearly relevant as it relates to the Appellant...<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Superior #1</EM> at p. 16.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>9. And so, for example, in <EM>Superior #1</EM> this Court did not order production of an unredacted version of Refused Document 16 (an intradepartmental communication) because &ldquo;the redacted information was not relevant to the Appellant and contained information relating to other taxpayers which is protected by section 241&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Superior #1</EM> at p. 21.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>10. Likewise, in <EM>Superior #1</EM>, this Court did not order production of unredacted versions of Refused Documents 17 and 18 (both interdepartmental communications between CRA and Finance) for the same reason noted for Refused Document 16.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Superior #1</EM> at p. 21 to 22.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>11. The FCA endorsed this Court's demarcation line of relevance in <EM>Superior #1</EM>, stating
<QUOTE><P>[8] ... However, relevance in the present case is no less established by the Tax Court judge's finding that the refused documents were either prepared in the context of the audit of Superior Plus or considered by officials who were involved in that audit (Reasons at para. 19).</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>12. In <EM>Superior #2</EM>, this Court further clarified the basis for ordering production. After noting that the taxpayer had disputed (in the Answer) whether the Minister actually relied on the existence of the policy (pleaded by the Crown in conformity to this Court's decision in <EM>Birchcliff Energy Ltd.</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Birchcliff Energy Ltd. v. The Queen</SOC><CITE>2012 CarswellNat 5540</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2013] 3 CTC 2169</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>TCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (<EM>Birchcliff</EM>).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>) and sought production of certain documents dealing with what was prepared in the context of the audit of the taxpayer or considered by the Minister's officials who were charged with that audit or consulted, Justice Hogan described the basis for ordering production:
<QUOTE><P>[2] I granted, in part, the Appellant's motion on the basis that, at the very least, the information sought could aid the Appellant in establishing that the Minister had not relied solely on the alleged policy or had not concluded that the impugned transactions clearly frustrated this policy.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Superior #2</EM>, citing para. 32 of the Reasons in <EM>Superior #1</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>13. It might, at first blush, be concluded that there were other bases for ordering production of certain documents in <EM>Superior #1</EM>. For example, this Court ordered production of Refused Document 4, an email between CRA and Finance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Superior #1</EM> at p. 17.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> But in <EM>Superior #2</EM> Justice Hogan described Refused Document 4 with more particularity, noting that it concerned the taxpayer:
<QUOTE><P>[40] These questions arise out of, and are logically connected to, the production of the email ... as redacted by the 2015 Order. They are relevant insofar as they go to the same issue as Document 4 did, that being the facts and circumstances surrounding the pleading of the policy. In the email, Mr. Adams cites the (at the time proposed) conversion of <UNDER>the Fund into what is now the Appellant</UNDER>, using an existing corporation, as an example of the loss-shifting transactions involving income funds that were causing the erosion of &ldquo;billions of dollars&rdquo; from the tax base.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Superior #2</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (underlining added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>14. In <EM>MP Western</EM>, Justice Miller applied the demarcation line established in <EM>Superior #1</EM>, where she stated:
<QUOTE><P>[28] Most recently, in <EM>Superior Plus No. 1</EM>, Hogan J. dealt with a very similar refusals motion in the context of a GAAR assessment where the policy behind the various Streaming Rules was at issue. In that case, Hogan J ordered the disclosure of all refused documents that either were prepared in the context of the taxpayer's audit or were considered by the CRA officials who had charge of the audit or who were consulted during the audit: <EM>Superior Plus No. 1</EM> at paragraph 19.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>15. Justice Miller acknowledged that, in a GAAR case, documents not specific to the taxpayer but relating to the policy of the <EM>Act</EM>, may be ordered to be disclosed in certain circumstances.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>MP Western</EM> at para. 29.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> However, such documents must still satisfy the demarcation line that they were either prepared in the context of the audit of the taxpayer or considered by officials who were involved in the audit of the taxpayer.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>MP Western</EM> at paras. 30-31.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Justice Miller ordered the production of one such document based on her finding of fact that the &ldquo;document was in Western's file and it was considered by CRA during the audit of Western&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>MP Western</EM> at para. 35 re document 20 and document 60 (document 20 and 60 were the same document).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. The appellant's submissions either ignore or skirt around the demarcation line established by this Court in <EM>Superior</EM>, as affirmed by the FCA, and as applied in <EM>MP Western</EM>.</P>
<P>17. Moreover, the FCA's decision in <EM>Lehigh</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Canada v. Lehigh Cement Limited</SOC><CITE>2011 FCA 120</CITE></CASEREF> (<EM>Lehigh</EM>).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> does not in conflict with the established and principled demarcation line in the context of an appeal involving the GAAR. This was made clear in the appeal in <EM>Superior #1</EM> where the FCA acknowledged that relevance could be admitted by conduct:
<QUOTE><P>[8] As was held by this Court in <EM>Lehigh Cement Ltd</EM>... in like circumstances, information pertaining to the policy of the Act, even where it is not taxpayer specific, can be relevant on discovery. We accept that an important consideration in that case was that the Crown had itself established the relevance of the documents by disclosing an internal policy memorandum on the subject (<EM>Lehigh</EM> at para. 41)...</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>18. Admitted relevance has no application here since no admission similar to that in <EM>Lehigh</EM> has been made by the Crown.</P>
<P>19. It is also important to put this Court's decision in <EM>Birchcliff</EM> in its proper context. <EM>Birchcliff</EM> is a &ldquo;pleadings case&rdquo; that sets out what a taxpayer is entitled to for purposes of pleading in a GAAR case. Several relevant points emerge or were summarized in <EM>Birchcliff</EM>:
<P1>a. The Crown must prove a policy in a GAAR case (para. 15). The Minister does not assume how the policy was abused as a fact (paras. 20 and 21). The policy is not a fact and certainly not an assumption. The policy is a question of law which the Court must ultimately determine (para. 18).</P1>
<P1>b. It is imperative that the Crown's reply set out as a material fact that the Minister relied on x or y policy underlying the provisions at play (para. 18). The policy must be disclosed in the reply, but not a treatise. It can be policy gleaned from a &ldquo;collective view&rdquo; (para. 19).</P1>
<P1>c. Abuse is not a question of fact but a determination to be made by the Court, having concluded what the policy is and whether the facts are such that they in some fashion abuse that policy (para. 20).</P1>
<P1>d. Although the policy may be argued differently at trial, the taxpayer is entitled to know&mdash;in the form of particulars and as a matter of pleading in the reply&mdash;the Minister's starting point. What the assessor relied upon in making the assessment does not bind the Crown (paras. 23 and 24).</P1></P>
<P>20. Moreover, in <EM>Birchcliff</EM>, the taxpayer wanted the Crown to identify precisely how the policy was abused. The Court said the request was made on the presumption the Minister assumed how the policy was abused as a fact and said this made no sense:
<QUOTE><P>21. What the Appellant wants is for the Respondent to identify precisely how the Policy was abused. The request is made on the presumption the Minister assumed how the Policy was abused as a fact. This makes no sense to me. The Minister did not assume how the Policy was abused as a fact. The Minister concluded, based on the Policy and the facts assumed, that there was an abuse, presumably in one or a combination of the three forms above. I cannot see how further particulars of facts can emanate from this interpretation.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>21. Here, the Crown pleaded in paragraph 12 of the Reply&mdash;post <EM>Birchcliff</EM>&mdash;in a summary way what the Minister considered to be the policy of the particular provisions under consideration for the GAAR analysis. Nowhere in the examination for discovery of the Crown's nominee did the appellant challenge or suggest that the Minister, as represented by the auditor, in reassessing the appellant, did not rely on or believe in the policy stated in paragraph 12.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Transcript of the examination of the auditor held on October 18, 2016 (the &ldquo;Discovery Transcript&rdquo;), Tab A of the Affidavit of Rosalind Semchuk. Counsel for the appellant specifically examined on paragraph 12 of the Reply, commencing at p. 49.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">III. Application of the Demarcation Line to the Requested Documents and Information</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The evidentiary record regarding the Requested Documents and Information</EM></TI>
<P>22. There is no evidence that any of the Requested Documents and Information were either prepared in the context of the audit of the appellant or considered by officials who were involved in that audit.</P>
<P>23. The appellant asked for (Discovery Request #2) and was provided with the entire &ldquo;audit file&rdquo; regarding the appellant.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Discovery Transcript at p. 19, lines 12 to 19 re Discovery Request #2 (Tab A of the Semchuk Affidavit); Crown's Answers to Undertakings (Tab B of Semchuk Affidavit) at p.1 re Discovery Request #2; Crown's Revised Answers to Undertakings (Tab C of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p.1 re Discovery Request #2; and Transcript of the follow-up examination of the auditor held on March 3, 2017 (the &ldquo;Follow-up Transcript&rdquo;) (Tab D of Semchuk Affidavit) at p.71, lines 25 to 27 re Discovery Request #2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>24. None of the Requested Documents and Information was in the audit file, even in redacted form.</P>
<P>25. Further, aside from the documents being requested in Motion Requests #1, 4, and 5, none of the other Requested Documents and Information is even <EM>referred to</EM> in any of the documents in the appellant's audit file.</P>
<P>26. The evidence from the examination for discovery regarding the Requested Documents and Information is as follows.</P>
<P>27. In Motion Request #1 (Discovery Request #4), the appellant seeks &ldquo;documents or information with respect to the GAAR committee's approval of the application of the GAAR&rdquo; to other taxpayers on the basis of the following excerpt from the proposal letter written by the auditor:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Discovery Transcript (Tab A of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 32, lines 3 to 11 and lines 20 to 24.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>The GAAR Committee has approved the application of the general anti-avoidance rule, the GAAR, to similar arrangements. Accordingly, we have applied Section 245(2) and (5) of the act to the CCAA planned transactions.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>28. The appellant incorrectly assumed that the auditor was in possession of or had considered documents and information regarding other SIFT conversion transactions during the course of his audit of the appellant.</P>
<P>29. The evidence of the auditor regarding those &ldquo;similar arrangements&rdquo; and the extent to which he had regard to them in his audit of the appellant was to the contrary, however, as described below:
<P1>a. the &ldquo;similar arrangements&rdquo; that are referred to in the August 26, 2015 letter are loss restart transactions and not SIFT conversion transactions;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 83, lines 2 to 16.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>b. the auditor was not aware of the specifics of any other cases that he wasn't dealing with;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Discovery Transcript (Tab A of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 15, lines 4 to 19.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>c. the auditor did not consider the positions taken by the CRA in other similar cases as he wasn't familiar with the facts of those other cases;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 77, line 23 to p. 78, line 6; p. 78, line 26 to p. 79, line 13.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>d. the auditor understood that the issues in his file had already been considered by the GAAR Committee;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Discovery Transcript (Tab A of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 31, lines 5 to 10; p. 25, lines 18 to 24; p. 26, lines 6 to 11; p. 26, line 21 to p. 27, line 10.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>e. but he had not seen anything specific from the GAAR Committee with respect to similar transactions;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Discovery Transcript (Tab A of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 22, line 25 to p. 23, line 4 and p. 24, lines 3 to 7.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>f. the auditor didn't need the approval of headquarters to propose utilizing the GAAR but only needed to know whether the issue had been considered previously by the GAAR Committee;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Discovery Transcript (Tab A of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 30, lines 17 to 27.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>g. the auditor was not aware of a &ldquo;blanket policy&rdquo; that the GAAR was applicable to all SIFT conversions involving loss companies;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Discovery Transcript (Tab A of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 17, lines 22 to 26.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>h. a GAAR referral was made by the auditor and a response was received from headquarters.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Discovery Transcript (Tab A of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 19, line 26 to p. 20, line 6; Followup Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 83, line 24 to p. 84, line 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The appellant asked for the recommendations of the GAAR Committee.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 84, line 24 to p. 85, line 14.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The auditor indicated that he did not see them,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 84, lines 22 to 23.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and the Crown took the request under advisement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Respondent's Answers to Undertakings at the Follow-Up Examination (Tab E of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 2 re Discovery Request #14.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> As it turned out, the GAAR Committee did not consider the auditor's referral and there were, therefore, no recommendations or minutes to produce relating to the appellant.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Respondent's Answers to Undertakings at the Follow-Up Examination (Tab E of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 2 re Discovery Request #14.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>30. In Motion Request #2 (Discovery Request #7), the appellant sought correspondence and documents between the CRA and Finance regarding changes or proposed changes to the Act on the issue of the application of the acquisition of control rules to SIFT conversions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Discovery Transcript (Tab A of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 46, line 27 to p. 47, line 18.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Aside from it being clear on its face that the request seeks evidence with respect to questions of law, the evidence at the discovery makes clear that none of the requested documents have any connection to the appellant:
<P1>a. The audit file did not contain any documents or correspondence between the auditor and anyone at Finance;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 74, line 22 to p. 75, line 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>b. Aside from the documents and sources referred to in the auditor's April 15, 2015 proposal letter in support of the auditor's assumed policy of the Act, the auditor did not rely on or review any other documents in arriving at his asserted policy of the Act.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Discovery Transcript (Tab A of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 43, line 24 to p. 44, line 9.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>31. In Motion Request #3 (Discovery Request #8), the appellant seeks production of certain documents that were ordered to be disclosed by Justice Hogan in <EM>Superior #1</EM>. The appellant marked pages 16 to 25 of the reasons of Justice Hogan in <EM>Superior #1</EM> as Exhibit A-4 at the examination and then requested that the highlighted documents be produced.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Discovery Transcript (Tab A of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 52, line 19 to p. 53, line 20 and see p. 28, lines 2 to 9; Exhibit A-4 at the examination of the auditor (Tab A1 of the Semchuk Affidavit). See also Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> After taking the request for production under advisement, the Crown refused to produce the documents that were highlighted on Exhibit A-4.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Respondent's Answers to Undertakings (Tab B of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 3 re Discovery Request #8.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There is no evidence or admission by the auditor that he had regard to or was ever in possession of any of the documents at issue in <EM>Superior #1</EM>.</P>
<P>32. With respect to Motion Request #4 (Discovery Request #12), in the audit file disclosed in response to Discovery Request #2, the Crown provided an email dated December 5, 2014, from Helen Little to the auditor (which was marked as Exhibit A-7 at the examination).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 75, lines 3 to 10 and p. 76, line 13 to 15.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The appellant seeks production of a memo that is referred to in that email. The email itself is not in the motion record. The only evidence with respect to that memo is that it is from headquarters CRA and contains comments regarding a settlement agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p.75, lines 20 to 25.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>33. With respect to Motion Request #5 (Discovery Request #16), in response to Discovery Request #5, the Crown had produced a number of documents evidencing discussions between the auditor and the GAAR and technical support section of CRA Headquarters, including a memorandum dated January 6, 2015.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Respondent's Revised Answers to Undertakings (Tab C of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 2 re Discovery Request #5; Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 83, lines 18 to 22. The memorandum was incorrectly dated January 6, 2015 and should have been dated January 6, 2016 (Respondent's Answers to Undertakings at the Follow-Up Examination (Tab E of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p.1 re Discovery Request #13.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>34. At the follow-up examination, the appellant asked to be advised of the correct date of the memo and to be provided with the recommendations of the GAAR Committee and the &ldquo;approval&rdquo; of the GAAR Committee referred to in the memo.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 85, lines 10 to 25 (Discovery Requests #14 and 15) and p. 86, lines 21 to 26 (Discovery Request #16).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In response, the Crown provided the correct date of the memo but refused to provide the recommendations or approval as they related to another taxpayer and there was no evidence the recommendation or approval was considered here by the auditor.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Respondent's Answers to Undertakings at the Follow-Up Examination (Tab E of the Affidavit of Rosalind Semchuk) at p. 2 regarding undertakings #14, 15 and 16.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>35. In this motion, the appellant merely seeks a copy of the &ldquo;approval&rdquo; of the GAAR Committee that is referred to in the memo (Motion Request #5, Discovery Request #16).</P>
<P>36. The evidence with respect to that January 6, 2015 memorandum and the &ldquo;approval&rdquo; is as follows:
<P1>a. The memo was received by the auditor in the course of his audit of the appellant and he relied on that memo in raising the assessments against the appellant;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 83, lines 24 to 27 and p. 84, lines 9 to 13.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>b. Although the memo refers to &ldquo;recommendations of the GAAR Committee&rdquo;, the auditor did not know what those were and had never seen them;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 84, lines 14 to 23.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and</P1>
<P1>c. The memo states that the &ldquo;GAAR Committee already approved the application of the GAAR to the SIFT conversion scheme&rdquo; but the auditor never had a copy of that approval.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 86, lines 4 to 15.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>37. With respect to Motion Requests #6 to 18, at the follow-up examination of the auditor, the appellant proceeded to go through Exhibit A-4 (the extract from the <EM>Superior #1</EM> decision) and asked the auditor regarding his knowledge of each of the highlighted documents and asked for an specific undertaking with respect to each that it be produced (those are Discovery Requests #17 to 29).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See Follow-up Transcript (Tab D of the Semchuk Affidavit): beginning at page 87 and continuing to page 98.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Crown refused to provide the documents.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>In the Respondent's Answers to Undertakings given at the Examination (Tab B of the Semchuk Affidavit at p.3 re Discovery Request #8), the Crown refused to provide the documents highlighted in Exhibit A-4. At the follow-up examination, in response to a request by the appellant for production of each specific document, the Crown refused to provide the document.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> With respect to each document, the auditor was asked the same series of three questions and gave the same evidence:
<P1>a. the auditor had not reviewed the document after the adjournment of the first round of the discovery;</P1>
<P1>b. the auditor was not aware whether the document dealt with a specific taxpayer; and</P1>
<P1>c. the auditor was not aware whether the document was created in the course of a specific audit of a particular taxpayer.</P1></P>
<P>38. Although not asked directly, it is nonetheless clear from the entire record that none of the documents being requested in Motion Requests #6 to 18 (Discovery Requests #17 to 29) dealt with the appellant, nor were they created in the course of the audit of the appellant, nor were they reviewed by the auditor in the course of his audit of the appellant.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Requested Documents and Information are not disclosable according to the demarcation line</EM></TI>
<P>39. The appellant's request for the Requested Documents and Information is an impermissible fishing expedition as it is not limited to documents and information that was either prepared in the context of the audit of the appellant or considered by officials who were involved in that audit. The appellant has already been provided with a copy of the audit file related to the appellant. Any further documents being sought by the Requested Documents and Information would be irrelevant on the basis of the demarcation line established in <EM>Superior #1</EM>, upheld by the Federal Court of Appeal and then applied in <EM>Superior #2</EM> and <EM>MP Western</EM>.</P>
<P>40. The appellant's reliance on this Court's decision in <EM>Dominion Nickel Investments Ltd.</EM> is misplaced.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Dominion Nickel Investments Ltd. v. The Queen</SOC><CITE>2015 TCC 14</CITE></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Justice Jorre utilized the same demarcation line established in <EM>Superior #1</EM>, upheld by the Federal Court of Appeal and then applied in <EM>Superior #2</EM> and <EM>MP Western</EM>. The disputed documents were found to be relevant and their production was ordered based on two findings, neither of which is present in our case:
<QUOTE><P>[46] I first note that there are two reasons which suggest that the documents in Exhibit R-2 are, <EM>prima facie</EM>, relevant to the appeal. First, they were produced in the respondent's list of documents under rule 81. The fact that they were produced in that list suggests that at some point the respondent thought that they were relevant to the appeal.</P>
<P>[47] Secondly, most documents, including the ones which are entirely redacted, have a cover sheet which has on it as a case name &ldquo;Dominion Nickel Investments Ltd.&rdquo;. Again this suggests that at some point these documents were thought relevant to this matter or, at least, they involved inquiries which were thought to be potentially relevant to this matter.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>41. Aside from the documents being requested in Motion Requests #1, 2, 4 and 4, the appellant's sole basis for the Requested Documents and Information is that the documents were ordered to be disclosed in <EM>Superior</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Discovery Transcript (Tab A of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 28, lines 2 to 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and both this case and <EM>Superior</EM> deal with the application of the GAAR to a SIFT conversion. But that is clearly insufficient and ignores that certain principles for disclosability (i.e., a demarcation line) were established and applied in <EM>Superior</EM>. The appellant seeks to avoid application of that demarcation line for good reason&mdash;unlike in <EM>Superior</EM> and <EM>MP Western</EM>&mdash;the requisite evidence is not present to satisfy it.</P>
<P>42. There is no evidence any of the Requested Documents and Information were either prepared in the context of the audit of the appellant or considered by officials who were involved in the audit of the appellant and no admission of relevance by the conduct of the respondent, unlike in <EM>Dominion Nickel</EM>. None of the Requested Documents and Information are producible and the motion should be dismissed.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">IV. Other Grounds for Refusals</TI>
<P>43. Even prior to the decisions in <EM>Superior</EM> and <EM>MP Western</EM>, this Court, when espousing the general principles applicable to discoveries, had recognized that the so-called &ldquo;audit file&rdquo; is producible at discovery.</P>
<P>44. As none of the Requested Documents and Information was part of the &ldquo;audit file&rdquo;, the demarcation line established in <EM>Superior</EM> is sufficient to deal with this motion.</P>
<P>45. However, there are other well-established discovery principles that also come into play and support the position that none of the Requested Documents and Information are producible:
<P1>a. A party is entitled to know the position of the other party as to an issue of law, but is not entitled to have access to either the legal research or the reasoning by which that position is arrived at.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Lloyd M. Teelucksingh v. The Queen</SOC><CITE>2010 TCC 94</CITE><PARANUM>15(ix)</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Kathryn Kossow v. The Queen</SOC><CITE>2008 TCC 422</CITE><PARANUM>60</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This would apply to support the position that Motion Requests #2, 3 and 6 to 18 are improper.</P1>
<P1>b. Documents that contain information that is subject to solicitor-client privilege are not producible unless there has been waiver of that privilege. This arises in respect of the following documents:
<P2>i. Motion Request #3 (Superior Refused Documents 23, 22, 21 and 6 referred to below);</P2>
<P2>ii. Motion Request #6 (Superior Refused Document 23 at p. 0034);</P2>
<P2>iii. Motion Request #7 (Superior Refused Document 22 at p. 0017);</P2>
<P2>iv. Motion Request #8 (Superior Refused Document 21);</P2>
<P2>v. Motion Request #16 (Superior Refused Document 6 at p. 1); and</P2>
<P2>vi. Motion Request #4.</P2></P1>
<P1>c. Documents concerning settlement are covered by settlement privilege and the privilege applies whether or not a settlement is reached.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Sable Offshore Energy v. Ameron International</SOC><CITE>2013 SCC 37</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF>. See also Justice Hogan's finding in <EM>Superior #1</EM> in respect of Refused Document 12 at p. 20.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This applies to the memo requested in Motion Request #4 and the document requested in Motion Request #6 (Superior Refused Document 23).</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">V. The Finance Request (Motion Request #2; Discovery Request #7)</TI>
<P>46. The appellant seeks production of any correspondence and documents between the CRA and Finance regarding changes or proposed changes to the Act on the issue of the acquisition of control rules to SIFT conversions (Motion Request #2; Discovery Request #7).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Discovery Transcript (Tab A of the Semchuk Affidavit) at p. 47, lines 10 to 18.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>47. The Finance Request is not specific to the appellant, or any taxpayer for that matter. There is no evidence any of the documents covered by the Finance Request were considered in issuing the reassessments at issue or were part of the audit file of the appellant.</P>
<P>48. On its face, the Finance Request is vague, overbroad and abusive as it does not name any areas of the CRA or individual authors or recipients of the correspondence requested and thus would seemingly require the respondent to make inquiry of all current and former employees of both the CRA and Finance.</P>
<P>49. This Court's decisions in <EM>Superior #1</EM> and <EM>MP Western</EM> illustrate how the request is irrelevant.</P>
<P>50. In <EM>Superior #1</EM>, this Court refused to order the production of Refused Documents 16 and 17 for the following reasons:
<P1>a. Refused Document 16 was an intradepartmental communication dated July 28, 2010 unrelated to the taxpayer regarding &ldquo;Tax Loss Trading&rdquo;. The Court held that the redacted information was not relevant to the taxpayer and also contained irrelevant taxpayer information protected by s. 241.</P1>
<P1>b. Refused Document 17 was an interdepartmental communication between the CRA and Finance dated February 18, 2008 regarding subsection 111(5). The Court held that the information should not be produced for the same reasons as those noted for Refused Document 16.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Superior #1</EM> at p. 21.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>51. In <EM>MP Western</EM>, this Court likewise held that the same interdepartmental communication between CRA and Finance dated February 18, 2008 (i.e., Refused Document 17 in <EM>Superior #1</EM> and Document 18 in <EM>MP Western</EM>) did not have to be produced as it was not specific to the appellants in <EM>MP Western</EM> and the redacted portions concerned irrelevant information of other taxpayers which is protected under s. 241.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>MP Western</EM> at p. 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>52. In Motion Requests #3 and 11 and 12, the appellant requests these same documents (i.e., Superior Refused Documents 16 and 17) that this Court held should not be produced. And the appellant is plainly wrong when it states in its written submissions that the documents requested in Motion Requests #11 (Superior Refused Document 17) and 12 (Superior Refused Document 16) &ldquo;were ordered to be produced&rdquo; in <EM>Superior #1</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See para. 50 of the appellant's written submissions.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>53. Moreover, in <EM>MP Western</EM>, the appellant's made an omnibus request, seeking the full record of the correspondence during the period 2001 to 2012 between the Department of Finance and the CRA, including emails, memos and letters, with respect to the CRA's perceived deficiency in the legislative scheme dealing with tax losses. Justice Miller refused the request, stating:
<QUOTE><P>Decision&mdash;...There was no evidence that any of these documents were prepared in the context of the Appellant's audit. There was evidence that only Document 20 was considered during the audit of Western. The Appellant's request is a &ldquo;fishing expedition of vague and far-reading scope&rdquo;. It is overly broad and it would be an onerous task to satisfy. Any documents obtained would contain the opinions of the writers who were not involved in the audit of the Appellants. This search does not have to be undertaken. The request is refused.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>MP Western</EM> at p. 16 re Request #6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>54. Justice Miller likewise denied another similar request in MP Western in which the appellants sought correspondence between the CRA and Finance with respect to the legislative scheme dealing with so-called corporate loss trading, tech wrecks or transfers of corporate losses.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>MP Western</EM> at p. 23 re Request #23.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>55. In addition, and aside from the statute-barred issue, the Notice of Appeal sets out the only other issue being whether section 245 applies to the transactions at issue.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Notice of Appeal, paragraph 51.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> No allegation or ground is raised in the Notice of Appeal regarding:
<P1>a. the policy of the Act,</P1>
<P1>b. whether the policy used in reassessing the appellant was correct (as opposed to just not applying on the facts), or</P1>
<P1>c. whether the policy changed as a result of the subsequent amendments.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Such matters were put in issue in <EM>Superior</EM> and <EM>MP Western</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>56. The only reason specified in the Notice of Motion as to why the appellant wants the Requested Documents and Information&mdash;the train of inquiry the appellant is following&mdash;is set out in paragraph 11 of the appellant's Motion:
<QUOTE><P>The train of inquiry is meant to determine whether the Policies alleged in the Reply clearly underlie the Streaming Provisions, SIFT Conversion Rules or the Act as a whole.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>57. As previously stated, in the Reply, consistent with this Court's finding in <EM>Birchcliff</EM>, the Crown set out the Minister's conclusions on the object, spirit and purpose of the provisions of the Act relied on by the Minister in issuing the reassessments at issue. These were not assumptions of fact in the sense of assumptions made by the Minister and presumed to be true unless <EM>prima facie</EM> demolished.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Birchcliffat</EM> para. 18.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>58. The object, spirit or purpose (or policy) of specific provisions is a question of law.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Canada Trustco Mortgage Co. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2005 SCC 54</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Canada Trustco</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 44. See also <EM>Superior #2</EM> at para. 79.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>59. In <EM>Superior #2</EM>, this Court made clear that the internal views and deliberations of Finance and what Finance believed to be a policy that underpins the Act are irrelevant to determining whether such a policy actually does exist.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Superior #2</EM> at paras. 77 and 78.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>60. Although the Crown is required to set out the policy with reference to the provisions of the Act upon which the Crown relies, ultimately, the Court must:
<P1>a. determine the object, spirit and purpose or policy of the provisions of the Act relied on for the tax benefit (having regard to the scheme of the Act, the relevant provisions and permissible extrinsic aids);<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Copthorne Holdings Ltd. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 63</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Copthorne&rdquo;)</EM> at para. 69 and <EM>Canada Trustco</EM> at para. 55.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and</P1>
<P1>b. consider whether the transactions fall within or frustrate the identified object, spirit or purpose of the provisions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Copthorne</EM> at para. 71 and <EM>Canada Trustco</EM> at para. 55.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>61. The reference to &ldquo;extrinsic aids&rdquo; is a reference to the comment of Rothstein J., as he then was, in <CASEREF><SOC>OSFC Holdings Ltd v. Canada</SOC></CASEREF>, that in determining the object and spirit of a particular provision for purposes of subsection 245(4) analysis it will be necessary to refer to extrinsic aids such as technical notes, writings, Hansard and enacting notes:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>OSFC Holdings Ltd. v. Canada</SOC><CITE>2001 FCA 260</CITE><PARANUM>63</PARANUM></CASEREF>; see also <CASEREF><SOC>Klaboe v. The Queen</SOC><CITE>2007 TCC 239</CITE><PARANUM>26</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>62. The common element amongst these aids is that they deal with the final version of the provision considered and enacted by Parliament, rather than a draft, and they are public statements and documents.</P>
<P>63. In <EM>Imperial Oil Ltd.</EM>, the Federal Court of Appeal recognized that permissible extrinsic aids were materials such as judicial statements, <EM>Hansard</EM>, ministerial or departmental statements, explanatory notes, bulletins, circulars, texts and periodicals:
<QUOTE><P>[49] One must infer from the statutory language the policy, if any, on which the relevant provisions of the Act are unambiguously based. This exercise in statutory interpretation must be undertaken with the assistance of such extrinsic aids as: judicial statements, <EM>Hansard</EM>, ministerial or departmental statements, explanatory notes, bulletins, circulars, texts, periodicals and others...<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Canada v. Imperial Oil Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2004 FCA 36</CITE><PARANUM>49</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>64. Not every comment, opinion, memorandum, departmental report or email is admissible as an aid to statutory interpretation. Intra-departmental memoranda and opinions of individual departmental officials do not reflect the intention of Parliament in enacting legislation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See Isaac CJ (in dissent) in <CASEREF><SOC>Owen Holdings Ltd. v. R</SOC><CITE>1997 CarswellNat 1012</CITE><COURTJUR>FCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 25.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>65. Likewise, it has been held that relying on out-of-legislature views and opinions of ministers and members of the legislature would be an unwarranted extension of the concepts underlying the court's resort to admissible extrinsic aids, as was stated in <CASEREF><SOC>Ontario Teachers' Federation v. Ontario (Attorney General)</SOC></CASEREF>.
<QUOTE><P>In my opinion, it would be an unwarranted extension of the concepts underlying the court's resort to aids such as Hansard, royal commission reports, government policy papers and other such sources bearing upon the history and background of the legislation, to broaden those concepts to apply to the sworn testimony and out-of-legislature views and opinions of ministers and members of the legislature. It would also be inconsistent with the weight of existing authority on the subject: ...<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><CITE>1998 CanLII 14680</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1998] O.J. No. 545</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>Ont. Gen. Div.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at p. 8.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>66. Questions regarding the amendment are also questions of law. At trial, the Court will have to consider whether the amendment indicates anything about the object, spirit and purpose of the pre-amendment provisions. In <CASEREF><SOC>Gwartz v. The Queen</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gwartz v. The Queen</SOC><CITE>2013 TCC 86</CITE></CASEREF> (<EM>Gwartz</EM>).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> this Court stated that a subsequent amendment must be considered along with all other relevant materials to ascertain the object, spirit, and purpose of the provision, noting that in certain circumstances a subsequent amendment might suggest that the provision's object, spirit and purpose was frustrated by the tax avoidance strategy. In other circumstances, however, this Court said it might be suggested that Parliament simply changed its mind and now intends to prevent something that initially was not intended to be captured by the provision.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Gwartz</EM> at para. 57.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>67. What is important, however, is that in considering the subsequent amendment, the usual rules will apply; the trial judge will have to consider the provisions of the Act and admissible extrinsic aids. The amendment does not make internal views or opinions of CRA and Finance officials relevant for the object, spirit and purpose analysis.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VI">VI. Taxpayer information</TI>
<P>68. Subsection 241 of the Act prohibits the disclosure of taxpayer information to a third party, subject to specific and limited exceptions. The scope of section 241 and the principles established in previous cases was considered in <CASEREF><SOC>9005-6342 Quebec Inc. v. The Queen</SOC></CASEREF>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><CITE>2010 TCC 463</CITE></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In that case, Justice Hogan determined that information protected by section 241 must meet the threshold requirement of relevance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>9005-6342 Quebec Inc.</EM> at para. 38.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In <EM>Superior #1</EM>, Justice Hogan similarly upheld redactions on the basis of section 241.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See for example, <EM>Superior #1</EM>, p. 17, re Refused Document 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>69. The appellant seeks production of numerous documents which contain unrelated taxpayer information which is not relevant. This arises in respect of the following documents:
<P1>a. documents requested in Motion Request #1</P1>
<P1>b. documents requested in Motion Requests #3 to 18 contain or are likely to contain taxpayer names or identifying information, in particular in respect of Superior Refused Documents 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 16, 17, 19, 21, 22, and 23.</P1></P>
<P>70. If any such documents are ordered to be disclosed, the respondent should be permitted to redact the portions containing taxpayer names or identifying information.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VII">VII. Application of the Principles</TI>
<P>71. Based on the forgoing, the Crown's submissions respecting each particular motion request is summarized in Schedule A attached.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VIII">VIII. Order Requested</TI>
<P>72. The Crown requests that the appellant's motion be dismissed with costs.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>DATED</BOLD> at the City of Vancouver, the Province of British Columbia, this 16th day of October, 2017.</P>
